<solution><div><h3><alert>Worked solution</alert></h3>
<br/><alert>Step 1:</alert> First, identify a vector that is parallel to the line, <m> (PQ) </m>.
<br/><alert>Recall:</alert> A vector that is parallel to the line  is <m> \vec{PQ} </m> or <m> \vec{QP} </m>.
<br/> <m> \vec{PQ} ({-3}, {-3}, {-4}) </m> 

<br/><alert>Step 2:</alert>  Picking either point will give you parametric equations for the line.
<br/>Here, let use <m>P</m> and a parameter <m> \alpha \in \mathbb{R}</m>. <m> \alpha </m> is typed as <alert>alpha</alert>
<br/> Let the point <m> M(x, y) \in (PQ) </m>, so <m> \vec{PM} </m>  and <m> \vec{PQ} </m> are colinear.
<br/> This means, there exists <m> \alpha \in \mathbb{R}</m>, such that  <m> \vec{PM} = \alpha \vec{PQ}  </m>
<br/> <m> \vec{PM} = \alpha \vec{PQ}  \implies {\left[\begin{array}{c} x-5 \\ y-2 \\ z-7 \end{array}\right]}={\left[\begin{array}{c} -3\cdot \alpha \\ -3\cdot \alpha \\ -4\cdot \alpha \end{array}\right]}</m>. Thus
<br/> <m> x= {5-3\cdot \alpha} </m>
<br/> <m> y= {2-3\cdot \alpha} </m>
<br/> <m> z= {7-4\cdot \alpha} </m>

<br/><alert>Step 2:</alert> Deduce the equations for the line passing through the points <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m>.
 <br/> Since <m> x= {5-3\cdot \alpha} </m> then <m> \alpha = \frac{{x-5}}{{-3}} </m>     
 <br/> Similarly  <m> y= {2-3\cdot \alpha} </m> then <m> \alpha = \frac{{y-2}}{{-3}} </m> 
 <br/>  and <m> z= {7-4\cdot \alpha} </m> then <m> \alpha = \frac{{z-7}}{{-4}} </m> 
<br/> Therefore, the equations of the line are:
<br/> <m> {-\frac{x-5}{3}}={-\frac{y-2}{3}}={-\frac{z-7}{4}} </m></div></solution>
